00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:56.240
Hello and welcome. I'm Jeffrey Mishlove. Today is&nbsp;
a special day. I'm here in Albuquerque with a live&nbsp;

00:01:56.240 --> 00:02:02.960
guest in my little studio. I'm with Chris Bache.&nbsp;
He has been interviewed several times on New&nbsp;

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:11.440
Thinking Allowed previously. Chris is an emeritus&nbsp;
professor from Akron State University in Ohio.&nbsp;

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:19.920
He is the author of several books including Life&nbsp;
Cycles, a book about reincarnation, Dark Night,&nbsp;

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:28.640
Early Dawn, The Living Classroom, and LSD&nbsp;
and the Mind of the Universe. Welcome, Chris.&nbsp;

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:30.880
Thank you, Jeff. It's a&nbsp;
pleasure to be here with you.&nbsp;

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:38.720
It's a real pleasure to be here with you in&nbsp;
person, in the flesh, after having watched so many&nbsp;

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:45.360
videos with you and having been on the live&nbsp;
stream with you as well. I thought today would&nbsp;

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:52.160
be an opportunity for our viewers, many&nbsp;
of whom will have watched these interviews&nbsp;

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:58.160
because they were quite popular, to get to&nbsp;
know you personally. I know, for example,&nbsp;

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:03.840
you've talked about your life a little bit.&nbsp;
At one time you were considering joining the&nbsp;

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:10.160
Catholic priesthood. Yeah, I was in the seminary&nbsp;
for four years, three years in high school and&nbsp;

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:15.920
one year in college. That's a very serious&nbsp;
commitment to enter the seminary while you're&nbsp;

00:03:15.920 --> 00:03:23.600
still in high school. So you had a Catholic&nbsp;
upbringing, obviously. A very kind of ecumenically&nbsp;

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:30.880
broad but strong Catholic upbringing down&nbsp;
in the deep south in Vicksburg, Mississippi.&nbsp;

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:39.440
My family comes from Louisiana on both sides, so&nbsp;
that French Catholic heritage down in New Orleans&nbsp;

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:47.920
area. So we were Catholic. I'll tell you, I don't&nbsp;
remember a time in my life when I didn't want to&nbsp;

00:03:47.920 --> 00:03:53.120
be a priest. I mean, when I kind of became aware,&nbsp;
became conscious, and certainly by the time I'm&nbsp;

00:03:53.120 --> 00:04:00.000
five years old, I remember having memories of&nbsp;
wanting to be a priest. It wasn't encouraged&nbsp;

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:07.680
by my family. It wasn't part of that. It just was&nbsp;
there in the beginning. So I went into seminary&nbsp;

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:12.960
as soon as I could in high school. They don't&nbsp;
have high school seminaries anymore because&nbsp;

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:19.440
they weren't really effective in yielding priests.&nbsp;
But I did. I went in the seminary and stayed in&nbsp;

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:25.600
until my freshman year in college and then&nbsp;
basically decided that celibacy and I weren't&nbsp;

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:32.480
cut out for each other and left. It's not as if&nbsp;
you left Catholicism at that point. No, I was at&nbsp;

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:39.440
Notre Dame and I got my degree in theology at&nbsp;
the University of Notre Dame. But by the time I&nbsp;

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:46.880
finished my undergraduate work, I was no longer&nbsp;
a Catholic in any normative sense. I went to&nbsp;

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:50.640
Cambridge and I studied New&nbsp;
Testament criticism. The search&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:57.680
for the historical Jesus was my earliest
academic love. By the time I left Cambridge,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:04.480
I really was no longer a Christian. The historical
Jesus actually was my way out of Christianity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:12.560
and into a larger world of spiritual teachers.
I see. What happened exactly? Well, I learned&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:19.840
Greek and Hebrew and all the languages one needs
to become a young scholar of New Testament. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.840 --> 00:05:24.560
search for the historical Jesus after several
years at undergraduate and then these two years at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:29.680
Cambridge, I think I got a pretty good grounding
of where research was taking us, where we were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.680 --> 00:05:37.680
going to be going in future years in that area.
I felt I had a good strong grounding in the best&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:46.480
historian's assessment of who this man was
and what was made of him. The theological&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:51.920
interpretations that followed really couldn't
capture, I think, or adequately convey the depth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.920 --> 00:06:00.480
and power of this person. I encountered in him
an intensity of spiritual awareness that was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:04.320
larger than the Christology&nbsp;
that I had internalized&nbsp;

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:08.960
and then when I began to study world religions&nbsp;
more broadly, I began to realize that there were&nbsp;

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:16.880
other beings who had this same deep quality&nbsp;
of spiritual connection. I never left&nbsp;

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:21.600
Christianity. I just opened up into a&nbsp;
larger family of religious discourse.&nbsp;

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:28.480
I taught world religions for decades. On the&nbsp;
arm of Houston Smith, his books were the ones&nbsp;

00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:35.040
that I used in my courses. So I would travel&nbsp;
the world every semester learning from the great&nbsp;

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:42.000
spiritual traditions of the world. Well, Houston&nbsp;
Smith was a good friend of mine. I did at least&nbsp;

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:50.480
half a dozen or more interviews with him. I got&nbsp;
to know him well in the days when I started doing&nbsp;

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:57.920
interviews in the San Francisco Bay area. To me,&nbsp;
he was a guiding light and a saint. He really was.&nbsp;

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:04.560
Probably next to Stan Grof, the single individuals&nbsp;
had the largest impact on my mind because I&nbsp;

00:07:04.560 --> 00:07:12.320
taught out of his books in world religions for so&nbsp;
many years. Wonderful man. Stan Grof was also a&nbsp;

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:18.960
big influence on you. Huge. When I finished my&nbsp;
graduate work in Brown in philosophy of religion&nbsp;

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:24.000
and I was looking for where to take my work&nbsp;
next, I encountered the work of two people&nbsp;

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:29.840
who had a huge impact on me. One was Ian&nbsp;
Stevenson at the University of Virginia,&nbsp;

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:36.000
his work in reincarnation. And he convinced me in&nbsp;
one reading of his book, 20 Cases Suggestive of&nbsp;

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:42.240
Reincarnation, that reincarnation is simply true.&nbsp;
It's just a fact. And that meant erasing seven&nbsp;

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:49.200
years of undergraduate and graduate school because&nbsp;
no other in my studies had reincarnation been&nbsp;

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:56.160
taken seriously, neither in the western religions&nbsp;
nor in the scientific traditions which had erased&nbsp;

00:07:56.160 --> 00:08:00.400
the western traditions in some ways&nbsp;
in my thinking. And so I had to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:04.000
start all over again and figure
out if reincarnation is true,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.600
what does that tell us about&nbsp;
the world we're living in? Well,&nbsp;

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:14.160
what does it mean by true? Yeah, I think it's just&nbsp;
a fact of nature. It's just an aspect of life.&nbsp;

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:18.640
There's so much we don't understand about&nbsp;
it. We don't understand the details of how&nbsp;

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:24.240
we don't understand anything about the&nbsp;
physics of the soul. But the phenomenology,&nbsp;

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:32.320
the phenomenological evidence shows us that our&nbsp;
mind predates our body and that our current life&nbsp;

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:40.320
is part of a tapestry of a much larger causal web&nbsp;
of lives stretching through time. And I began to&nbsp;

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:46.080
understand that if you don't understand&nbsp;
reincarnation, then you can't understand much&nbsp;

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:52.000
that's happening in this world. It's like trying&nbsp;
to take one chapter out of a Sherlock Holmes novel&nbsp;

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:57.280
and trying to understand the entire book and all&nbsp;
you have is that one chapter. We need the other&nbsp;

00:08:57.280 --> 00:09:03.680
chapters to really understand the things that led&nbsp;
into this life and what we're studying in this&nbsp;

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:12.800
starting in this life continuing on in other&nbsp;
lifetimes. Do you seem to feel that everybody&nbsp;

00:09:12.800 --> 00:09:17.360
has a chain of historical&nbsp;
incarnations that they've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.360 --> 00:09:24.960
experienced? Well, in general, I think so. But
of course, there have to be beginners somewhere.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:30.720
There have to be people in their first lifetime
or second or third lifetime. And then it's like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:34.000
at a university. There are freshmen
and there are seniors and there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.120
are people who have been at this&nbsp;
game for a longer period of time.&nbsp;

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:43.760
And the spiritual traditions often refer to those&nbsp;
as old souls. That's a metaphor for someone who's&nbsp;

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:49.200
gathered sufficient experience that they've&nbsp;
spiritually matured over the course of their&nbsp;

00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:54.960
lifetimes. I would imagine as a student of&nbsp;
theology there would be in the literature&nbsp;

00:09:54.960 --> 00:10:02.000
many other options besides reincarnation. Yeah,&nbsp;
they are. But this to me is not a theological&nbsp;

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:07.200
proposition. I mean, for a long time it was&nbsp;
discussed in theological or philosophical&nbsp;

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:12.800
terms and debated. But I think in the last 50&nbsp;
years it's moved from the theologian's table&nbsp;

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:18.080
to the psychologist's table. It's become a matter&nbsp;
of empirical research. And the empirical research&nbsp;

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:23.440
I think is overwhelming. So the first book&nbsp;
I wrote was my response to Ian Stevenson.&nbsp;

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:29.920
And there I just basically my conviction is we&nbsp;
have overwhelming empirical evidence. Stevenson's&nbsp;

00:10:29.920 --> 00:10:34.080
research and the research on&nbsp;
coming out of past life therapy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:39.200
Roger Woolger, for example, and other
past life therapists. Cumulatively there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:44.880
is sufficient evidence to make this the most
reasonable hypothesis for understanding life. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.880 --> 00:10:50.960
that conviction is only deepened in my psychedelic
work and in my other studies through the years.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.960 --> 00:10:55.600
And that brings me to the second person that I
encountered both in my first year when I was just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:55.600 --> 00:11:02.080
beginning my academic career was Stan Grof. His
book, Realms of the Human Unconscious, which had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:07.840
just been published then, was a turning point for
me. When I read it I immediately recognized that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:14.320
Stan's work was incredibly important not just for
psychology and therapy, but for philosophy, my&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:21.600
discipline. And I knew I needed, I wanted to get
involved in this. I felt a calling. And I knew&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:26.880
that, I felt that the people who would be doing
the most important work in my field of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:30.640
philosophy of religion would be&nbsp;
speaking out of an experiential&nbsp;

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:36.720
basis, not simply a theoretical basis. And I knew&nbsp;
it would take time, it would take a long time&nbsp;

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:43.920
to really do serious work in the area. So I&nbsp;
settled in in 1979 and it began as a course of&nbsp;

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:51.280
LSD therapy following Stan's protocols. And that&nbsp;
ended up lasting much longer than I had expected.&nbsp;

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:57.680
It ended up lasting 20 years of active work. In&nbsp;
fact, I'd have to say I think of you as one of&nbsp;

00:11:57.680 --> 00:12:06.320
the foremost psychonauts, if I can use that term,&nbsp;
of whom I'm aware you took it very methodically,&nbsp;

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:14.560
very seriously over years, keeping careful records&nbsp;
of your experiences and with a clear idea of the&nbsp;

00:12:14.560 --> 00:12:19.440
goal. Well you know, yeah,&nbsp;
and many misunderstandings and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:23.680
misinterpretations. I mean I had a limited
understanding of the psyche and a limited&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:29.520
understanding of how this work would proceed
and those had to fall away over time. But in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:34.720
beginning, well let me back up, I had been
practicing meditation for years since&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:34.720 --> 00:12:38.080
undergraduate work and in through&nbsp;
graduate school. Had started&nbsp;

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:44.080
with transcendental meditation and then moved into&nbsp;
Vipassana meditation and had experienced the usual&nbsp;

00:12:44.080 --> 00:12:50.000
blocks that people have in the first years of&nbsp;
their meditation practice. And when I met Stan's&nbsp;

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:55.040
work I thought, oh here's a way in which I can&nbsp;
push through these blocks faster, I could burn up&nbsp;

00:12:55.040 --> 00:13:02.960
my karma faster, and I would get on the other&nbsp;
side and I would become enlightened faster. Well&nbsp;

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:10.400
that's not the way it kind of worked out because&nbsp;
I came to understand that the fundamental model&nbsp;

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:15.920
we were using in the transpersonal community&nbsp;
was still a model of personal transformation,&nbsp;

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:22.000
that you did your work, you encountered, you sort&nbsp;
of cleansed your own karma, you dealt with your&nbsp;

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.200
past lives, you cleared up your inner baggage,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:30.640
and then you would move into some heightened
state of spiritual sensitivity. Like you're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:33.680
finished. Yeah, we'll come&nbsp;
enlightened, and that was&nbsp;

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:39.520
you know, but what happened was not that. And I&nbsp;
think it was partly because of the very aggressive&nbsp;

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:46.000
protocol I adopted. Now Stan outlines&nbsp;
two protocols, psycholytic therapy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.280
low dose, where you peel the
psyche layer by layer, piece&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:54.800
by piece, and high dose psychedelic&nbsp;
therapy, where in the Spring Grove&nbsp;

00:13:54.800 --> 00:14:03.520
program in Maryland they were using high dose&nbsp;
therapy for to address anxiety, death anxiety,&nbsp;

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:10.000
among people who were terminally ill. It was&nbsp;
limited to three sessions. So coming along later&nbsp;

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.760
I thought, well if you could do it safely three&nbsp;
times, you could do it safely more times. And&nbsp;

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:20.240
because I was married at the time, and soon there&nbsp;
would be children coming along, and it was hard to&nbsp;

00:14:20.240 --> 00:14:24.240
get time away from dual career&nbsp;
family for a weekend of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:30.080
type of deep inner work, I decided to do
psychedelic therapy, working with high doses,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:35.920
thinking I would, if I could maintain the
stability needed to work creatively and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:39.600
productively at these high states,&nbsp;
I would basically chew up my&nbsp;

00:14:39.600 --> 00:14:46.240
karma faster. I would clean my plate faster. But&nbsp;
what happened, of course, is if you work with&nbsp;

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:53.520
highly amplified states of consciousness, pretty&nbsp;
soon you just shatter the boundaries of your&nbsp;

00:14:53.520 --> 00:14:59.680
personal psyche, so the working dynamic becomes&nbsp;
larger than anything which could be explained&nbsp;

00:14:59.680 --> 00:15:05.200
in terms of your personal psyche, even your&nbsp;
personal enlightenment. Within a couple of years&nbsp;

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:10.480
I was being drawn into vast experiential&nbsp;
territories that really didn't have too much&nbsp;

00:15:10.480 --> 00:15:16.080
to do with me personally, and over time&nbsp;
I came to understand that I was engaging&nbsp;

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:22.880
what you might think of as co-ec systems or&nbsp;
systems of condensed experiences within the&nbsp;

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:28.640
collective psyche, what I called metacoec&nbsp;
systems, that there was some way in which&nbsp;

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:36.480
my individual work had been changed into&nbsp;
serving not my personal clarification,&nbsp;

00:15:36.480 --> 00:15:42.720
but somehow contributing a small piece to the&nbsp;
clarification of the human psyche as a whole,&nbsp;

00:15:42.720 --> 00:15:48.880
to the collective unconscious. Are you suggesting&nbsp;
then that you had personal issues that did not&nbsp;

00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:54.720
get addressed? Oh no, they got addressed both&nbsp;
before and after that work. So it wasn't a&nbsp;

00:15:54.720 --> 00:16:00.800
spiritual bypass. No, if you keep coming&nbsp;
back over and over again sooner or later,&nbsp;

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:06.000
the universe is going to clean you up. It may&nbsp;
clean you up in the beginning using one protocol,&nbsp;

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:13.600
it'll clean you up later using another protocol,&nbsp;
but if you keep engaging the deep energy of life,&nbsp;

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:18.000
it's going to bring out all your shadow&nbsp;
material, all your former life material,&nbsp;

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.320
it's going to release you&nbsp;
from the pains that bind you.&nbsp;

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:32.640
So that happened and then you entered into this&nbsp;
state, I guess one way to put it, and if I recall&nbsp;

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:41.120
you used the phrase the consciousness of&nbsp;
humanity. Yes. What I found was that when the&nbsp;

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:47.520
bubble of your personal psyche pops, you know,&nbsp;
and that egoic bubble pops and is no longer the&nbsp;

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:54.560
organizing matrix for your experience, you don't&nbsp;
simply pop into unitive non-dual consciousness.&nbsp;

00:16:54.560 --> 00:17:01.280
There are many layers of consciousness between&nbsp;
your individual ego and unitive consciousness,&nbsp;

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:06.880
so the consciousness of God or something like&nbsp;
this. There is all these layers of the collective&nbsp;

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:13.920
unconsciousness, the mind of the species, the&nbsp;
psyche of the species, and early on in my work,&nbsp;

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:18.720
when I was transitioning after I'd gone through&nbsp;
what Stan would have described as a classic&nbsp;

00:17:18.720 --> 00:17:24.720
perinatal death-rebirth process where&nbsp;
my individual psyche was just shattered,&nbsp;

00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:32.880
then I went through an experience where I was&nbsp;
confronting the killing of thousands and thousands&nbsp;

00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:40.160
of children, just being mauled and maimed by&nbsp;
soldiers, and I was powerless to be able to&nbsp;

00:17:40.160 --> 00:17:46.320
stop it. And I think this was an awakening&nbsp;
of what the Buddhists would call bodhicitta,&nbsp;

00:17:46.320 --> 00:17:51.840
the desire to save all sentient beings.&nbsp;
And the way I came to understand it later,&nbsp;

00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:58.080
I didn't understand it at the time, it was&nbsp;
basically reminding me of a commitment that&nbsp;

00:17:58.080 --> 00:18:06.400
I had made before I was born, what my incarnation&nbsp;
was about. And it was basically awakening my&nbsp;

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:12.480
compassion so that I would do anything, if&nbsp;
given the opportunity, to save the children,&nbsp;

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:19.600
to save the lives of the children. And then&nbsp;
began a two-year process of entering into this&nbsp;

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:24.880
ocean of suffering in the cleansing portion of&nbsp;
the sessions. Of course, there is the ecstatic&nbsp;

00:18:24.880 --> 00:18:30.640
portion and the cleansing portion, but in the&nbsp;
cleansing portion there's this huge deeper and&nbsp;

00:18:30.640 --> 00:18:36.960
deeper and deeper experience of the terrible&nbsp;
suffering that still resides within the collective&nbsp;

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:41.840
psyche. All the things that we've done to each&nbsp;
other, all the wars and the killing and the being&nbsp;

00:18:41.840 --> 00:18:47.200
killed and all the rapes and all the droughts and&nbsp;
all the suffering of humanity, anything which is&nbsp;

00:18:47.200 --> 00:18:55.520
unresolved in any individual's life by the time&nbsp;
they die, accumulates in the psyche. And just as&nbsp;

00:18:55.520 --> 00:19:03.920
our individual trauma compromises our individual&nbsp;
clarity, our collective trauma compromises our&nbsp;

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:11.360
collective clarity. And for some reason, a large&nbsp;
portion of my work for those years involved&nbsp;

00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:16.240
draining some of that toxicity out of the&nbsp;
collective psyche. And I don't think there's&nbsp;

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:20.560
anything unique to me and certainly nothing&nbsp;
unique to psychedelics about that work. I think&nbsp;

00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:28.720
there are many, many beings at all sorts of&nbsp;
levels who are working primarily in service&nbsp;

00:19:28.720 --> 00:19:35.120
of healing the collective psyche to make humanity&nbsp;
more able to take advantage of the shifts of&nbsp;

00:19:35.120 --> 00:19:41.360
energy that are coming to us in history. Because&nbsp;
I would think if you're in touch with the psyche&nbsp;

00:19:41.360 --> 00:19:48.720
of humanity in addition to the enormity of the&nbsp;
pain and the suffering, the needless pain and&nbsp;

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:56.800
suffering, the cruel heartless pain and suffering,&nbsp;
there are also many things to feel differently&nbsp;

00:19:56.800 --> 00:20:05.920
about the ambitions of people, the visions&nbsp;
that people have, the joy that people have, the&nbsp;

00:20:05.920 --> 00:20:12.160
creativity that has been expressed in art and&nbsp;
music and literature. Yeah, and the genius.&nbsp;

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:19.440
What happened for me is that in the first&nbsp;
year of experiencing the ocean of suffering,&nbsp;

00:20:19.440 --> 00:20:26.000
when I would go through the crisis and go through&nbsp;
a breaking point and surrender to that, then I was&nbsp;

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:33.200
taken for the first time into what I came to call&nbsp;
deep time. And I was taken for a year and seven&nbsp;

00:20:33.200 --> 00:20:40.880
sessions. I experienced my entire life from&nbsp;
beginning to end as a single totality. And I&nbsp;

00:20:40.880 --> 00:20:49.040
was given an set of insights into what my life&nbsp;
was about, into personal relationships that I was&nbsp;

00:20:49.040 --> 00:20:55.440
involved in, about my work at the university.&nbsp;
But it was very kind of personal. It was at the&nbsp;

00:20:55.440 --> 00:21:00.960
psychic level of transpersonal experience. And&nbsp;
then I stopped my work for six years for reasons&nbsp;

00:21:00.960 --> 00:21:06.720
I described in the book. And when I resumed a&nbsp;
year, six years later, the ocean of suffering&nbsp;

00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:11.360
began exactly where it had stopped, and it kept&nbsp;
getting deeper and deeper, worse and worse.&nbsp;

00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:18.080
But what was happening in the ecstatic portion of&nbsp;
those sessions is that I entered what I call the&nbsp;

00:21:18.080 --> 00:21:21.760
initiation into the universe.&nbsp;
I was being initiated,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:25.200
I was like I was given a crash course in Cosmology&nbsp;

00:21:25.200 --> 00:21:33.040
101, being given a series of experiences that far&nbsp;
transcended my individual life and opened me to&nbsp;

00:21:33.040 --> 00:21:40.240
some of the fundamental metaphysical truths&nbsp;
of existence. In that process, as that process&nbsp;

00:21:40.240 --> 00:21:47.040
continued to deepen, I kept being immersed in the&nbsp;
collective psyche of humanity. And I was being&nbsp;

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:55.120
basically taught, I've always had a sense of being&nbsp;
guided in my sessions by a higher intelligence&nbsp;

00:21:55.120 --> 00:22:02.880
a higher consciousness that never manifested&nbsp;
in any figure or form. It never adopted a form,&nbsp;

00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:10.800
it was always invisible, but it was always there,&nbsp;
always guiding me and instructing me. And so I&nbsp;

00:22:10.800 --> 00:22:18.080
dissolved in the collective psyche repeatedly and&nbsp;
was taught the ways in which our individual minds&nbsp;

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:25.680
are part of our species mind. Even our individual&nbsp;
diseases are part of the collective diseases that&nbsp;

00:22:25.680 --> 00:22:32.880
we are processing in history. And that everything&nbsp;
we do individually, both the acquisition of our&nbsp;

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:40.400
problems and the solution of those problems, come&nbsp;
from and radiate back into the collective psyche.&nbsp;

00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:48.080
And even our diseases come out of our humanity's&nbsp;
stage of our evolutionary history. And as we&nbsp;

00:22:48.080 --> 00:22:52.640
heal those diseases, that healing goes&nbsp;
out and ripples out into the collective.&nbsp;

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:58.480
And that's the primary thing I was addressing&nbsp;
in Dark Night Early Dawn. I was beginning to&nbsp;

00:22:58.480 --> 00:23:05.840
understand that there is no such thing as private&nbsp;
karma. It's all collective karma in the end,&nbsp;

00:23:05.840 --> 00:23:12.880
just as there's no separate private identity, but&nbsp;
always an interconnected web work of identity.&nbsp;

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:18.480
There is no such thing as private karma. We're&nbsp;
always drawing from and feeding back into the&nbsp;

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:23.680
karma of our species. We're all growing together.&nbsp;
We're all arm and arm. We're all developing it&nbsp;

00:23:23.680 --> 00:23:27.600
together. And this was sort of&nbsp;
laid out for me over and over,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:27.600 --> 00:23:32.240
clarity and clear and clear instructions.
And it's very interesting. I mean,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:32.240 --> 00:23:35.840
it would take me through a series&nbsp;
of instructions and then double&nbsp;

00:23:35.840 --> 00:23:41.200
back and take me through it again and again until&nbsp;
it was sure that I understood. And then we would&nbsp;

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:45.840
go on to the next lesson. As if&nbsp;
you were following a curriculum.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:45.840 --> 00:23:50.000
It was. And it was not a curriculum
of my own making. It didn't come&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:53.920
out of my studies. It didn't come&nbsp;
out of my reading. It was the only&nbsp;

00:23:53.920 --> 00:24:00.320
teacher I've ever had. And the only spiritual&nbsp;
teacher I've ever had has been the universe,&nbsp;

00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:06.480
out of this kind of profound encounter and&nbsp;
communion, and then surrendering and let it&nbsp;

00:24:06.480 --> 00:24:11.760
teach me whatever it wanted me to know. On the&nbsp;
one hand, you're learning from the universe,&nbsp;

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:18.560
and on the other hand, it's being facilitated&nbsp;
by a very particular molecule. Yeah. Isn't that&nbsp;

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:26.640
interesting? Yeah. And of course we have hundreds,&nbsp;
thousands of molecules we find in nature that&nbsp;

00:24:26.640 --> 00:24:30.320
facilitate these amplified states&nbsp;
of consciousness. It just happens&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:30.320 --> 00:24:35.760
that LSD happens to be a synthesized
version that came from Albert Hofmann's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:43.600
work. But the fundamental dynamic is the same. It
amplifies consciousness for a few hours at a time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:43.600 --> 00:24:48.640
and how you use that amplified state
determines whether you're just having&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:55.040
an enjoyable afternoon with the Grateful Dead,
or whether you're having a spiritually cleansing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:55.040 --> 00:25:02.400
purifying process that then opens you up into some
of the deeper currents of the divine life. Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:09.840
it's very clear from your background which path
you chose. I assume you weren't exactly a party&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:17.520
animal. No. You know, I left the priesthood,
but in some ways the priesthood never left me.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:23.120
And then as I learned more about the Eastern
traditions and my meditation practice deepened,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:23.120 --> 00:25:26.480
and I was teaching courses&nbsp;
on comparative mysticism&nbsp;

00:25:26.480 --> 00:25:33.840
and advanced courses on Buddhism, I just I&nbsp;
always considered the spiritual teachers from&nbsp;

00:25:33.840 --> 00:25:39.840
multiple religious traditions to be my mentors and&nbsp;
trying to live up to the examples that they gave&nbsp;

00:25:39.840 --> 00:25:48.800
us. In your LSD sessions and the layers that you&nbsp;
described, I would imagine that the next obvious&nbsp;

00:25:48.800 --> 00:25:56.320
layer after the consciousness of humanity as&nbsp;
a whole, which is huge, would be the ecosystem&nbsp;

00:25:56.320 --> 00:26:03.280
of the planet that we share because our species&nbsp;
is not isolated either. Absolutely. But it's&nbsp;

00:26:03.280 --> 00:26:08.640
interesting. My work didn't go in that direction.&nbsp;
Many people's do, especially I think when they're&nbsp;

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:15.440
using organic psychedelics like psilocybin or&nbsp;
ayahuasca. Many people have deep experiences of&nbsp;

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:25.600
the deeper web work of life and the fabric of&nbsp;
life. Mine didn't. And over time, the best I've&nbsp;

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:33.040
been able to understand why it went the way it&nbsp;
went and didn't go is because humanity forms&nbsp;

00:26:33.040 --> 00:26:40.240
the greatest danger to life on this planet.&nbsp;
We are the problem. And my work seemed to be&nbsp;

00:26:40.240 --> 00:26:47.200
really narrowly focused on helping transform,&nbsp;
helping humanity transform its consciousness.&nbsp;

00:26:47.200 --> 00:26:53.440
And if humanity can come to a clarity and&nbsp;
resolution of its of its negative karma and&nbsp;

00:26:53.440 --> 00:26:59.840
the spiritual awakening, then the planet will&nbsp;
be safe. The planet will can be revived, will be&nbsp;

00:26:59.840 --> 00:27:05.920
safe because we will not use our intellect in a&nbsp;
way which is at the expense of other life forms.&nbsp;

00:27:05.920 --> 00:27:12.160
So I didn't go laterally. I just I kind of went&nbsp;
deeper. So what happened when I kind of after&nbsp;

00:27:12.160 --> 00:27:16.320
spending years working at the&nbsp;
collective level, I went through&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:16.320 --> 00:27:22.480
a process where I went through another
cycle of birth and death. In the beginning,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:22.480 --> 00:27:27.600
I thought, oh, you go through ego death,
and that's the death. And then you enter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:27.600 --> 00:27:34.720
into transpersonal reality, spiritual reality.
What I found is that that's not quite so easy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:34.720 --> 00:27:41.040
that there are multiple layers of death that you
go to, go through as you go into deeper and deeper&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:41.040 --> 00:27:44.560
layers of the universe. So&nbsp;
after I had been working&nbsp;

00:27:44.560 --> 00:27:51.680
kind of at the collective layer for some time, I&nbsp;
went through a process where my entire identity&nbsp;

00:27:51.680 --> 00:27:59.760
as a human being began to fall away from me.&nbsp;
And I found that we have we have an identity&nbsp;

00:27:59.760 --> 00:28:06.080
which is deeper than our personal identity. And&nbsp;
just as ego death, your personal identity falls&nbsp;

00:28:06.080 --> 00:28:13.440
away, still you have a human identity which is&nbsp;
underneath. And that began to fall away. And when&nbsp;

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:21.040
that came fall away, all the stories, all the&nbsp;
mythologies, all the theologies, all the religions&nbsp;

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:29.600
of the world fell away. And I entered into states&nbsp;
of consciousness that were radically beyond&nbsp;

00:28:29.600 --> 00:28:36.800
human history. It was as if it had the quality&nbsp;
of like being in the space station, international&nbsp;

00:28:36.800 --> 00:28:43.120
space station far above the earth. And all the&nbsp;
details of the earth are just fallen away. And&nbsp;

00:28:43.120 --> 00:28:50.560
I was in a world of extraordinary quiet,&nbsp;
stillness. And then a new round of teaching began.&nbsp;

00:28:50.560 --> 00:28:56.720
And the new round of teaching was taking me into&nbsp;
archetypal reality, the layers of reality that&nbsp;

00:28:56.720 --> 00:29:05.600
that are beyond the layers that stand in between&nbsp;
the unit of source for which all life springs,&nbsp;

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:11.840
and yet it unfolds in layers. And some of those&nbsp;
layers we call archetypal, not one layer, but&nbsp;

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:17.200
multiple layers. They structure, they manifest,&nbsp;
they create time and space, they manifest time&nbsp;

00:29:17.200 --> 00:29:24.080
and space. They're the fundamental constitutive&nbsp;
processes that lead to time and space as we know&nbsp;

00:29:24.080 --> 00:29:31.760
it. And then I spent a couple years working there.&nbsp;
Well, that's very interesting. I had a mentor&nbsp;

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:40.080
years ago, Arthur M. Young, who was a cosmologist&nbsp;
and an inventor. And he would sometimes&nbsp;

00:29:40.080 --> 00:29:48.160
poke us with a question. It was, how do you&nbsp;
reconcile being a single unique individual&nbsp;

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:56.000
separate from everything and at the same time&nbsp;
one with everything? Yeah, that is the paradox,&nbsp;

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:02.800
isn't it? And he said the answer is in what&nbsp;
he called the realm of mythos, mythology,&nbsp;

00:30:02.800 --> 00:30:07.760
or the archetypal realm is the&nbsp;
realm that connects the two.&nbsp;

00:30:07.760 --> 00:30:14.160
Interesting. Yeah, I can understand that.&nbsp;
You know, in some spiritual traditions,&nbsp;

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:21.360
they sacrifice the individual and the vision is&nbsp;
that when you achieve realization of spiritual&nbsp;

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:27.760
awakening, you dissolve as a drop in the ocean,&nbsp;
you return to the ocean, the drop dissolves,&nbsp;

00:30:27.760 --> 00:30:33.600
and you are now one with the divine and there is&nbsp;
no more individual separate individual at all.&nbsp;

00:30:33.600 --> 00:30:42.160
But that's not been my experience. My experience&nbsp;
has been that the boundaries of the individual&nbsp;

00:30:42.160 --> 00:30:48.960
are radically expanded. The commerce with the&nbsp;
surround is radically expanded. There is no&nbsp;

00:30:48.960 --> 00:30:54.800
separate individuality, but there is nevertheless&nbsp;
an individuality. I've come to believe that&nbsp;

00:30:54.800 --> 00:31:00.160
individuality is one of the great gifts&nbsp;
that the physical universe gives us&nbsp;

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:07.920
and that gift is not simply to be returned&nbsp;
when we make contact with the unity of reality,&nbsp;

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:14.240
but actually there is a there is&nbsp;
a suffusion that union actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:14.240 --> 00:31:19.040
requires a highly developed
individuality to sustain it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:24.160
and then individuality allows us to&nbsp;
enter to grow and be nourished by this&nbsp;

00:31:24.160 --> 00:31:31.040
communion and to become a deeper kind of&nbsp;
individuality than we were at earlier stages.&nbsp;

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:37.600
But always there is this, there are these&nbsp;
two fundamental truths, the truth of oneness&nbsp;

00:31:37.600 --> 00:31:43.760
and the truth of individuality which shares&nbsp;
and receives and that interconnected truth that&nbsp;

00:31:43.760 --> 00:31:48.960
Buddhism emphasizes so much, the&nbsp;
truth of interdependent co-arising.&nbsp;

00:31:48.960 --> 00:31:55.840
Interdependent co-arising. It's as if&nbsp;
this is the self-creation of the universe.&nbsp;

00:31:55.840 --> 00:32:00.800
Yes, and we are part of that. We're part of the&nbsp;
manifestation. We're part of its evolutionary&nbsp;

00:32:00.800 --> 00:32:10.480
journey and we are its children and&nbsp;
we are an edge as it explores itself.&nbsp;

00:32:11.120 --> 00:32:17.760
Here's where I get stuck a little bit and I&nbsp;
think maybe you can help me through this impasse.&nbsp;

00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:24.480
If you're dealing in the archetypal realm, as&nbsp;
you've described, to my understanding all of&nbsp;

00:32:24.480 --> 00:32:28.720
the archetypes that we know&nbsp;
are expressed in human terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:28.720 --> 00:32:35.680
– the father archetype, the mother archetype,
the hero and so on – but you're also saying that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:35.680 --> 00:32:41.360
you move beyond human terms. So how do the
archetypes manifest when you're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:41.360 --> 00:32:50.960
beyond the human side of things?
Good question. You know, I experienced archetypes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:50.960 --> 00:32:55.920
that affirmed Jung's understanding of the
collective psyche, but I didn't experience&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:55.920 --> 00:33:00.960
archetypes the way he describes archetypes.
I didn't experience the wise old man or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:07.200
the wise woman or the trickster. I didn't
experience archetypes in that form. I'm not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:12.160
saying they don't exist, it's just not how I
experienced it. The other major voice&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:12.160 --> 00:33:16.560
in archetypes is Plato, who&nbsp;
conceptualized archetypes as&nbsp;

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:22.560
unchanging ideas in the mind of an eternal&nbsp;
being. So they are the blueprints, the unchanging&nbsp;

00:33:22.560 --> 00:33:28.240
blueprints which are used in creation, and I&nbsp;
didn't experience archetypes that way either.&nbsp;

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:35.200
I experienced archetypes as vast, massive&nbsp;
beings living on a different order of time,&nbsp;

00:33:35.200 --> 00:33:41.040
a different order of reality, so vast that I&nbsp;
literally could not wrap my mind around them.&nbsp;

00:33:41.040 --> 00:33:48.560
I could not see them. The closest I could come&nbsp;
to seeing them, my mind imaged them as galaxies,&nbsp;

00:33:48.560 --> 00:33:56.400
you know, just vast, completely different order,&nbsp;
and not static, like galaxies moving very slow&nbsp;

00:33:56.400 --> 00:34:03.600
relative to a solar system spin, but deliberately&nbsp;
and on a different scale of existence. And that's&nbsp;

00:34:03.600 --> 00:34:08.240
how I experienced archetypes,&nbsp;
not human, not in any human form,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:08.240 --> 00:34:14.720
profoundly transcended to the human
project, and yet crystallizing the human project&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:14.720 --> 00:34:20.880
as their own intention. So the basic image that
comes down, it's kind of classic Sri Aurobindo&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:20.880 --> 00:34:27.440
kind of image, where the one cascades into layers
and layers and layers, and some of those layers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:27.440 --> 00:34:33.920
we called archetypal. And I guess if we get down
to the lower layers, we may find wise old man,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:33.920 --> 00:34:39.440
wise old woman, those human forms. But at the
deeper levels, we're looking at the cosmic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:39.440 --> 00:34:46.720
principles of creation, the living beings that
kind of manifest time and space and orders within&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:46.720 --> 00:34:52.160
time and space. But I only spent about a year and
a half touching these realities,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:52.160 --> 00:34:56.560
which is a pittance, I mean, you&nbsp;
know, in no way an exhaustive&nbsp;

00:34:56.560 --> 00:35:03.440
account of them. And then I was moved on into&nbsp;
another layer, even beyond the archetypes, beyond&nbsp;

00:35:03.440 --> 00:35:08.480
the archetypes, beyond the&nbsp;
archetypes, because the archetypes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:08.480 --> 00:35:16.400
emerge out of a deeper level of reality,
a non-dual, a unitive, a oneness that births&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:23.840
existence, you know, the primal void out of which
the Big Bang emerges. Archetypes come, I won't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:23.840 --> 00:35:31.440
want to say they come later, but they come,
there's a distance between the one which is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:31.440 --> 00:35:40.080
origin, and then where we are, where everything,
not the 10,000 pieces, as the Tao Te Ching says,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:40.080 --> 00:35:45.920
the 10,000 beings. But&nbsp;
yeah, beyond the archetypes.&nbsp;

00:35:45.920 --> 00:35:53.120
And it was after I went through the archetypes&nbsp;
and after I had begun to experience some of the&nbsp;

00:35:53.120 --> 00:36:02.080
early stories of the way that humanity functions&nbsp;
as a single organism, I began to have experience&nbsp;

00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:09.760
there of reincarnation, not of individual souls.&nbsp;
I had some extraordinarily broad experiences of&nbsp;

00:36:09.760 --> 00:36:17.120
experiencing the entire human family pulsing&nbsp;
in reincarnation. Every hundred years or so,&nbsp;

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:23.760
another generation coming in and dying, living&nbsp;
their lives, and I began to experience that there&nbsp;

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:32.240
is a genuine sense in which it's not only&nbsp;
individuals who reincarnate, but individuals or&nbsp;

00:36:32.240 --> 00:36:39.600
cells within the body of humanity which is&nbsp;
incarnating and growing and becoming more&nbsp;

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:46.800
collectively, but as a body, as a single&nbsp;
being, and we are all parts of that being,&nbsp;

00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:52.240
and there is no private karma within this being,&nbsp;
there is only the pulsing and nourishing of&nbsp;

00:36:52.240 --> 00:37:00.080
collective karma as we grow individually, as&nbsp;
it grows unitively as a species on this little&nbsp;

00:37:00.080 --> 00:37:09.120
piece of the corner of the galaxy. And then after&nbsp;
spending time in that territory, I went into a&nbsp;

00:37:10.240 --> 00:37:16.000
year of experiences in the book I call the&nbsp;
Benediction of Blessings. It was just a cascade&nbsp;

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:24.320
of extraordinarily deep experiences that we&nbsp;
recognize from the mystical traditions. One of&nbsp;

00:37:24.320 --> 00:37:31.920
them, for example, was a deep experience of&nbsp;
Śūnyatā, emptiness of self, and where there is&nbsp;

00:37:31.920 --> 00:37:37.520
no self inside of you, you're experiencing the&nbsp;
world and its diversity, but there's no self here,&nbsp;

00:37:37.520 --> 00:37:43.680
there's no self there, there's no self anywhere.&nbsp;
The whole system is living and breathing as one,&nbsp;

00:37:43.680 --> 00:37:50.960
just it's a living experience of oneness,&nbsp;
and that's why I began to understand that&nbsp;

00:37:50.960 --> 00:37:57.200
no self and oneness were two different sides of&nbsp;
the same coin, because if you have the experience&nbsp;

00:37:57.200 --> 00:38:02.800
of no self, then you naturally open up into&nbsp;
the oneness of life, and if you open into the&nbsp;

00:38:02.800 --> 00:38:08.000
oneness of life, then you experience&nbsp;
the transparency of all supposedly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:11.280
separate selves, there are no
separate selves, everything is&nbsp;&nbsp;

